This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Hughes Creek Catchment.

  • MODERATE FLOODING EASING ALONG HUGHES CREEK AT TARCOMBE ROAD
  • MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING ALONG ACHERON RIVER AND THE GOULBURN RIVER AND TRIBUTARIES UPSTREAM OF LAKE EILDON
  • MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE AT SEYMOUR THURSDAY NIGHT
  • Rainfall totals of 50-115 mm have been observed since 9 am Wednesday in the Goulburn River catchment due to heavy showers and thunderstorms with a cold front.
  • Minor flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River and tributaries upstream of Seymour and may extend downstream to Seymour from overnight Thursday into Friday.
  • The situation is being closely monitored and predictions will be revised as required.
  • Moderate flooding is easing along the Hughes Creek at Tarcombe Road.


Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.

Impacts in your area:

  • A small number of properties are may become isolated due to floodwater. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 09/06/2023 01:00 pm or as the situation changes.

properties.webBody:
This is a Final Flood Watch for the Upper Murray and Mitta Mitta Rivers .

FLOOD RISK HAS EASED IN PARTS OF NORTHERN VICTORIA

A rainband which has moved across the state over the last 36 hours is now passing through Gippsland and easing, with some light to moderate showers remaining around higher peaks

Widespread rainfall totals of 40-100 mm was observed in the 24 hours to 9 AM today, with higher falls up to around 140 mm in parts of the mountains. Since 9 am, a further 15-40 mm fell in alpine parts.
Catchments across northeastern Victoria are now wet.

No further flood producing rain is expected.Flooding is no longer expected in the Upper Murray and Mitta Mitta River catchments.

A Severe Weather Warning for heavy rainfall has been cancelled.

The threat of flooding for the Upper Murray and Mitta Mitta Rivers has passed, but be aware of any hazards that may still exist in the warning area. 
The threat of flooding is reduced. You can now return to normal activity, but be aware of any hazards that may still exist in the warning area.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

This will be the last warning issued for this flood.

MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE AT KIALLA WEST FRIDAY MORNING

Since 9am Wednesday, rainfall totals of 70-120 mm have been observed across the Seven and Castle Creeks catchment due to showers and thunderstorms associated with a cold front. 

Moderate flooding has eased along Seven Creeks at Strathbogie and Galls Gap Road. Minor flooding is also occurring at Euroa and is likely to exceed the moderate flood level Thursday evening. Further river level rises are possible. 
The situation is being closely monitored and predictions will be revised as required.

Castle Creek: River levels are elevated along the Castle Creek to Telfords Bridge.

Seven Creeks downstream of Euroa: Moderate flooding may occur along the Seven Creeks downstream of Euroa. The Seven Creeks at Kialla West is currently at 2.54 metres and rising. below the minor flood level. The Seven Creeks at Kialla West may exceed the minor flood level (4.50 m) overnight Thursday into Friday. The river level may reach the moderate flood level (5.00 m) Friday morning.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Rising floodwater can be dangerous. Be aware of water levels rising near you.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.

Impacts in your area:

  • Minor flood level at 4.50m Mitchell Road likely to be flooded between Goulbourn Valley Highway and Archer Street

  • Moderate flood level at 5.00m Raftery Road, Kialla likely to be flooded between the bridge and Edgewater Road. Arcadia Downs traffic likely to be detoured due to floodwater.

  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
